[30;1m224 | [0m[35m    Converts a sequence of unstructured Element objects to an OntologyElement object.[0m
[30;1m225 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m226 | [0m[35m    The function caches the elements in a dictionary and each element is assigned to its parent.[0m
[30;1m227 | [0m[35m    At the end the root element is popped from the dictionary and returned.[0m
[30;1m228 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m229 | [0m[35m    Such approach comes with limitations:[0m
[30;1m230 | [0m[35m        - The parent element has to be in the list before the child element[0m

[30;1m142 | [0m[35m "combined" iterator[0m
[30;1m143 | [0m[35m        # -- return value using `yield from`. You can think of the return value as an Element[0m
[30;1m144 | [0m[35m        # -- stream and each `yield from` as "add elements found by this function to the stream".[0m
[30;1m145 | [0m[35m        # -- This is functionally analogous to declaring `elements: List[Element] = []` at the top[0m
[30;1m146 | [0m[35m        # -- and using `elements.extend()` for the results of each of the function calls, but is[0m

[30;1m148 | [0m[35m        # -- those small lists), is more flexible for later iterator operations like filter,[0m

[30;1m1192 | [0m[35m        """Page-break behavior has some subtleties.[0m
[30;1m1193 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m1194 | [0m[35m        * A hard page-break does not generate a PageBreak element (because that would double-count[0m
[30;1m1195 | [0m[35m          it). Word inserts a rendered page-break for the hard break at the effective location.[0m
[30;1m1196 | [0m[35m        * A (rendered) page-break mid-paragraph produces two elements, like `Text, PageBreak, Text`,[0m
[30;1m1197 | [0m[35m          so each Text (subclass) element gets the right page-number.[0m

[30;1m361 | [0m[35m        # -- return value using `yield from`. You can think of the return value as an Element[0m
[30;1m362 | [0m[35m        # -- stream and each `yield from` as "add elements found by this function to the stream".[0m
[30;1m363 | [0m[35m        # -- This is functionally analogous to declaring `elements: list[Element] = []` at the top[0m
[30;1m364 | [0m[35m        # -- and using `elements.extend()` for the results of each of the function calls, but is[0m
[30;1m365 | [0m[35m        # -- more perfomant, uses less memory (avoids producing and then garbage-collecting all[0m
